    "body": "### Problem\r\n\r\nIn some circumstances `g<Up>` and `g<Down>` forgot the cursor column.\r\n\r\n### Steps to reproduce\r\n\r\nStart `nvim`:\r\n\r\n    nvim -u NONE\r\n\r\nRemap `i_<Up>` to `<Cmd>normal g<Up><CR>`:\r\n\r\n    :lua vim.keymap.set('i', '<Up>', '<Cmd>normal g<Up><CR>')\r\n\r\nIn a new buffer:\r\n      - Add an empty line\r\n      - Edit the line below the empty line\r\n      - Type `<Up>` (which we have remapped)\r\n      - Type `<Down>`\r\n      - The column is lost\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n### Expected behavior\r\n\r\nThe behavior should be same as if `<Up>` was not remapped: the cursor should come back to its initial location.\r\n\r\nNote this behavior does not happen if you map with:\r\n\r\n    :lua vim.keymap.set('i', '<Up>', '<C-o>:normal g<Up><CR>')\r\n\r\n(however, it's damn slow)\r\n\r\n### Neovim version (nvim -v)\r\n\r\nv0.8.2 and v0.9.1\r\n\r\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\r\n\r\nN/A\r\n\r\n### Operating system/version\r\n\r\nDebian Bookworm\r\n\r\n### Terminal name/version\r\n\r\nkonsole\r\n\r\n### $TERM environment variable\r\n\r\nxterm-256colors\r\n\r\n### Installation\r\n\r\nDebian package (0.8) and Appimage (0.9) provided by github.",
